==In popular culture==
* The 1982 French-Italian film [http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0084423/combined La Nuit de Varrenes] is about a fictional meeting of [[Giacomo Casanova|Casanova, Chevalier de Seingalt]] (played by Italian actor [[Marcello Mastroianni]]), [[Restif de la Bretonne|Nicolas Edm<U+00E9> Restif de la Bretonne]], Countess Sophie de la Borde, and Thomas Paine (played by American actor [[Harvey Keitel]]) as they ride in a carriage a few hours behind the carriage carrying the King and Queen of France, [[Louis XVI of France|Louis XVI]] and [[Marie Antoinette]], on [[Flight to Varennes|their attempt to escape from revolutionary France]] in 1791.

* [[Jack Shepherd (actor)|Jack Shepherd]]'s stage play ''In Lambeth'' dramatized a visit by Thomas Paine to the [[Lambeth]] home of [[William Blake|William]] and [[Catherine Blake|Catherine]] Blake in 1789, first performed at the East Dulwich Tavern in London in July 1989.<ref>[http://archive.tribunemagazine.co.uk/article/8th-september-1989/9/partisan-polemics] ''[[Tribune (magazine)|Tribune]]'': "Partisan Polemics", 8 September 1989</ref><ref>[http://www.lewestheatre.org/Productions/Synopsis/Production/20/Season/6] Lewes Theatre Company: ''In Lambeth''</ref> The play was later adapted for television in the [[BBC Two]] ''Encounters'' series - which featured similar fictionalized meetings between historical figures - and was first broadcast on 4 July 1993. It was directed by Sebastian Graham-Jones, and featured [[Bob Peck]] as Paine, [[Mark Rylance]] as William, and Lesley Clare O'Neill as Katherine (sic).<ref>''[[Radio Times]]'' 3<U+2013>9 July 1993, page 50.</ref>

* In 2001 the Scottish musician [[Dick Gaughan]] included the song "Tom Paine's Bones" on his album ''Outlaws and Dreamers''.

* In 2005 the writer [[Trevor Griffiths]] published 'These are the Times: A life of Thomas Paine', originally written as a screenplay for [[Richard Attenborough]] productions. A film has not been made but it was broadcast as a two-part radio drama on [[BBC Radio 4]] in 2008<ref>http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006qgxs/broadcasts/2008/08</ref> with a repeat in 2012 [http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006qgxs/broadcasts/2012/08]. In 2009 Griffiths adapted his screenplay for a production titled "[[A New World: A Life of Thomas Paine|A New World]]" at [[Shakespeare's Globe]] theatre on London's South Bank.<ref>http://www.shakespearesglobe.com/education/discovery-space/previous-productions/new-world</ref>

* In 2009, Paine's life was dramatized in a play 'Thomas Paine Citizen of the World' [http://www.keystage-company.co.uk/Keystage_Arts_and_Heritage_Company/Project_Portfolio/Entries/2009/4/27_THOMAS_PAINE_-_CITIZEN_OF_THE_WORLD.html], produced for the "Tom Paine 200 Celebrations" festival<ref name="tompainlegacy">[http://www.tompainelegacy.org.uk/programme.html Tom Paine Legacy], Programme for bicentenary celebrations.</ref> in [[Thetford]], the town of his birth.

* Paine's role in the foundation of the United States is depicted in a pseudo-biographical fashion in the educational animated series [[Liberty's Kids]] produced by [[DIC Entertainment]].

* Paine is a character in the [[Bob Dylan]] song [[As I Went Out One Morning]], featured on Dylan's 1968 album, [[John Wesley Harding (album)|John Wesley Harding]].

* Paine is also mentioned in the song [[Renegades of Funk]] by [[Afrika Bambaataa]] in which he is referred to as "Tom Paine" among other notable "renegades" [[Chief Sitting Bull]], [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] and [[Malcolm X]]. The song was later done as a cover by the rap metal band [[Rage Against the Machine]], with Paine's name still being mentioned.

