===Bibliography===

* [[A. Owen Aldridge|Aldridge, A. Owen]], 1959. ''Man of Reason: The Life of Thomas Paine.'' Lippincott. Regarded by British authorities as the standard biography.
*Aldridge, A. Owen, 1984. ''[http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lN582EPgp40C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Owen+Aldridge#v=onepage&q=&f=false Thomas Paine's American Ideology]''. [[University of Delaware Press]].
* [[Alfred Jules Ayer|Ayer, A. J.]], 1988. ''Thomas Paine''. [[University of Chicago Press]].
* [[Bernard Bailyn|Bailyn, Bernard]], 1990. "Common Sense", in Bailyn, ''Faces of Revolution: Personalities and Themes in the Struggle for American Independence''. Alfred A. Knopf.
* [[Richard B. Bernstein|Bernstein, R. B.]] "Review Essay: Rediscovering Thomas Paine". ''New York Law School Law Review,'' 1994 <U+2013> valuable blend of historiographical essay and biographical/analytical treatment.
* [[Marilyn Butler|Butler, Marilyn]], 1984. ''Burke Paine and Godwin and the Revolution Controversy''.
* [[Gregory Claeys|Claeys, Gregory]], 1989. ''[http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=10lR6gi5sswC&printsec=frontcover&dq=claeys+thomas+paine#v=onepage&q=&f=false Thomas Paine, Social and Political Thought]''. Unwin Hyman. Excellent analysis of Paine's thought.
* [[Moncure D. Conway|Conway, Moncure Daniel]], 1892. ''The Life of Thomas Paine'', 2 vols. G.P. Putnam's Sons, [http://books.google.com/books?id=Ja4FAAAAMAAJ&source=gbs_navlinks_s Vol. 1 (E'book)], [http://books.google.com/books?id=nPZi9BDUHhAC&source=gbs_navlinks_s Vol 2 (E'book)]. Long hailed as the definitive biography, and still valuable.
* [[Howard Fast|Fast, Howard]], 1946. ''Citizen Tom Paine'' (historical novel, though sometimes mistaken as biography).
* Ferguson, Robert A.  "The Commonalities of Common Sense", ''William and Mary Quarterly,'' July 2000, Vol. 57#3 pp 465<U+2013>504 [http://www.jstor.org/stable/2674263 in JSTOR]
* [[Eric Foner|Foner, Eric]], 1976. ''Tom Paine and Revolutionary America''. [[Oxford University Press]]. The standard monograph treating Paine's thought and work with regard to America.
* [[Eric Foner|Foner, Eric]], 2000, "Paine, Thomas" in [http://www.anb.org.proxy.cc.uic.edu/articles/16/16-01251.html ''American National Biography Online''] 
*{{Cite journal|last=Griffiths|first=Trevor|authorlink=Trevor Griffiths|year=2005|title=These Are the Times: A Life of Thomas Paine|publisher=Spokesman Books|postscript=<!--None-->}}
* Hawke, David Freeman, 1974. ''Paine''. Regarded by many American authorities as the standard biography.
* [[Christopher Hitchens|Hitchens, Christopher]], 2006. ''[[Thomas Paine's "Rights of Man": A Biography]]''.
* Kates, Gary, 1989, "From Liberalism to Radicalism: Tom Paine's Rights of Man", ''Journal of the History of Ideas'': 569<U+2013>587.
* [[Harvey J. Kaye|Kaye, Harvey J.]], 2005. ''Thomas Paine and the Promise of America''. Hill and Wang.
* [[John Keane (political theorist)|Keane, John]], 1995. ''Tom Paine: A Political Life''. London. One of the most valuable recent studies.
* Lamb, Robert. "Liberty, Equality, and the Boundaries of Ownership: Thomas Paine's Theory of Property Rights". ''Review of Politics,'' Summer 2010, Vol. 72 Issue 3, pp 483<U+2013>511
* Larkin, Edward, 2005. ''[http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=-XnIqhEl7VAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=larkin+thomas+paine#v=onepage&q=&f=false Thomas Paine and the Literature of Revolution.]'' Cambridge University Press.
* Lessay, Jean. L'am<U+00E9>ricain de la Convention, Thomas Paine: Professeur de r<U+00E9>volutions. Paris, <U+00E9>ditions Perrin, 1987, 241 p.
* Levin, Yuval. ''The Great Debate: Edmund Burke, Thomas Paine, and the Birth of Right and Left'' (Basic Books; 2013) 275 pages; their debate over the French Revolution. 
* [[Joseph L. Lewis|Lewis, Joseph L.]], 1947, "Thomas Paine: The Author of the Declaration of Independence". Freethought Association Press Assn.: New York.
* Nelson, Craig, 2006. ''Thomas Paine: Enlightenment, Revolution, and the Birth of Modern Nations''. Viking. ISBN 0-670-03788-5.
* Philip, Mark, 2004. "Paine, Thomas (1737<U+2013>1809)," ''Oxford Dictionary of National Biography'' Oxford University Press, 2004; online edn, May 2008 [http://www.oxforddnb.com.proxy.cc.uic.edu/view/article/21133  accessed 16 Dec 2013];  doi:10.1093/ref:odnb/21133 
* Powell, David, 1985. ''Tom Paine, The Greatest Exile''. Hutchinson.
* {{Cite journal|last=Russell|first=Bertrand|authorlink=Bertrand Russell|year=1934|title=The Fate of Thomas Paine|postscript=<!--None-->}}
* Solinger, Jason D. "Thomas Paine's Continental Mind". ''Early American Literature,'' Nov 2010, Vol. 45 Issue 3, p593-617
* Vincent, Bernard, 2005. ''[http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=1ZRoDgG2vQ0C&printsec=frontcover&dq=bernard+vincent#v=onepage&q=&f=false The Transatlantic Republican: Thomas Paine and the age of revolutions]''.
* {{Cite book|last=Wilensky|first=Mark|year=2008|title=The Elementary Common Sense of Thomas Paine. An Interactive Adaptation for All Ages|publisher=Casemate|isbn=978-1-932714-36-4|postscript=<!--None-->}}
* Washburne, E. B. [http://archive.org/stream/scribnersmonthly20newy#page/770/mode/2up "Thomas Paine and the French Revolution"]. Scribner's Monthly, Vol. XX, May/October 1880.

===Primary sources===
*{{cite book |last=Paine |first=Thomas |editor-last=Conway |editor-first=Moncure Daniel |ref=Paine |title=The Writings of Thomas Paine, Volume 4 |publisher=<br>G. P. Putnam's sons, New York |year=1896 |pages=521 |isbn=}}, [http://books.google.com/books?id=srpGH65Zl9kC&vq=kosciuszko&source=gbs_navlinks_s E'book]
*[[Michael Foot|Foot, Michael]] and [[Isaac Kramnick|Kramnick, Isaac]], eds. (1987). ''The Thomas Paine Reader''. Penguin Classics. ISBN 0-14-044496-3
* Paine, Thomas ([[Eric Foner|Foner, Eric]], editor), 1993. ''Writings.'' Library of America. Authoritative and scholarly edition containing ''Common Sense,'' the essays comprising the ''American Crisis'' series, ''Rights of Man,'' ''The Age of Reason,'' ''Agrarian Justice,'' and selected briefer writings, with authoritative texts and careful annotation.
* Paine, Thomas ([[Philip Foner|Foner, Philip S.]], editor), 1944. ''The Complete Writings of Thomas Paine,'' 2 volumes. Citadel Press. We badly need a complete edition of Paine's writings on the model of Eric Foner's edition for the Library of America, but until that goal is achieved, Philip Foner's two-volume edition is a serviceable substitute. Volume I contains the major works, and volume II contains shorter writings, both published essays and a selection of letters, but confusingly organized; in addition, Foner's attributions of writings to Paine have come in for some criticism in that Foner may have included writings that Paine edited but did not write and omitted some writings that later scholars have attributed to Paine.

